@mernst Thanks for noticing this!
So it looks like we can probably never remove a class. Even a private inner class can have a public subclass within the same outer class:
import org.checkerframework.checker.nullness.qual.Nullable;
class Demo {
    private class Internal {
        public void foo(@Nullable Object p) {}
    }
    public class Public extends Internal {}

    void bar(Public p) {
        p.foo(null);
    }
}
The public inner class could get exposed, so we need to keep it to maintain annotations from it.
Similarly, for AbstractStringBuilder, even though nobody from outside the package can refer to that class, there can be visible subclasses.
I'll remove that line for classes.
We kind-of have the same problem with methods: if a package-private method uses an inheritable annotation (like @Pure), the method affects overriding methods that might become public.
So we should also stop removing package-private methods.
It's still fine to remove private methods, because they cannot be overridden.
Removing private and package-private fields still seems ok to me.
Any other cases I'm missing?

